title: For Sale:  FN SCAR 17 17S .308
postcontent: Brand New In The Box FN SCAR 17S all Black with one 20 round magazine, telescopic and folding stock, flip up sights and the owner’s manual. At last, the SCAR 17S is here. The new rifle is a semi-automatic-only version of the military’s selective-fire MK17 Mod 0 or Special Ops Combat Assault Rifle (SCAR) Heavy. Chambered in .308 Win./7.62x51 mm NATO, the gun is bigger and more powerful than its .223 Rem./5.56x45 mm NATO predecessor, the SCAR 16S, but, thankfully, not objectionably so. No longer constrained by limitations of that gun’s smaller receiver and chambering, the bigger SCAR 17S greatly expands the potential utility of the SCAR platform. One can argue that the SCAR Heavy was what Special Operations Command (SOCOM) wanted all along: a modern carbine chambered in 7.62x51 mm NATO that is lightweight, reliable and accurate.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Leather IWB holster for Ruger SP101
postcontent:
This is a like new holster that came with the LCR I just purchased. I wasn't totally happy with the fit and instead of attempting to stretch it out, I did some bing and google searches which indicate that it is for the Ruger SP101 and not the LCR which has a slightly oversized trigger guard. The guy I purchased the LCR from was really nice but I believe he purchased this because it is for a 2" Ruger revovler an didn't realize that the SP101 and the LCR are shaped a little differently. It is brown and looks exactly like the one in this picture. A few of the links I found when I googled the holster indicate that it may also work with a Charter Arms revolver. It might but I believe it is really designed for the SP101. This looks to me to be a quality holster but I am very particular about the trigger guard being covered and I think it would work better for someone with an SP101. title: For Sale:  AES-10B Romanian RPK Squad Heavy-Barreled Weapon - Excellent Condition
location: Aurora - Alameda and I225, Denver, Colorado
postcontent:
Available at Firing Line in Aurora

This is not a normal AK. This is a heavy barrel squad weapon designed for extended fire and higher accuracy. Design includes a flip-down carrying handle, folding heavy-duty steel stock, rear windage adjustable sight and heavy duty stamped receiver.

Design details:
Operating mechanism - The AES-10B RPK functions identically to the AK-47. It also uses the same 7.62x39mm ammunition. It has a similar design layout to the AK-47 series of rifles, with modifications to increase the RPK's effective range and accuracy, enhance its sustained fire capability, and strengthen the receiver.

Features - Most notably, the AES-10B RPK has a heavier and longer barrel (23.5") than an AK. This allows the AES-10B RPK to fire for extended periods of time without major loss in accuracy due to the barrel heating up. The chrome-lined barrel is permanently fixed to the receiver, and cannot be replaced in the field. It is fitted with a new front sight base, gas block (lacks the bayonet lug) and an under-barrel cleaning rod guide. The barrel also features a folding bipod, mounted near the muzzle. The barrel's muzzle is threaded, enabling the use of muzzle devices such as flash hiders, compensators, and blank-firing adapters. When a muzzle device is not being used, the threads on the muzzle can be covered by a thread protector. The barrel is pinned to the receiver in a modified trunnion, reinforced by ribbing, and is slightly wider than the trunnion used on standard AK type rifles. Symmetrical bulges on both sides of the front trunnion ensure proper fit inside the receiver.

The AES-10B RPK's receiver cover is stamped from a smooth 1.5 mm (0.1 in) sheet of steel (compared to the 1 mm sheet metal receiver cover used on standard AK rifles). Interchangeability of parts between the RPK and AKM is moderate.

The AES-10B RPK uses a modified AKM recoil spring assembly. It consists of a rear spring guide rod from the AK, and a new forward flat guide rod and coil spring.

The RPK features a thick wood foregrip, and a folding steel buttstock, which is designed to allow the user to carry and store more easily. The RPK uses a standard AK pistol grip.

The weapon can use standard AK detachable box magazines, but is most commonly used with a 40 round capacity magazine, or a 75 round drum magazine.

Sights - The weapon's rear sight leaf is elevation adjustable, and graduated for ranges of 100 to 1,000 meters, in 100 m increments. The rear sight leaf also features a windage adjustment knob, unique to the RPK series of rifles.

For Sale:  Daewoo DP51 9mm Auto
location: MYRTLE BEACH/SURFSIDE, Myrtle Beach, South Carolina
postcontent:
This Daewoo is in very good condition.  It is the DP51 9mm pistol.  It features a matte black finish, 3 dot sights, ambi safety and a unique tri action trigger system.  It can fire in both the traditional DA and SA mode plus the hammer can be cocked and then pushed forward for a light double action trigger pull.  Includes 1 13 round magazine, no box. solid gun. Never have had an issue with it. Fun to shoot.$350 cash must have S.C id REDACTED


REDACTED


Little background on the gun:

In the 1990, after the excessive trials, South Korean army adopted the first domestically designed 9mm pistol, the K5. Developed and manufactured in Korea by the Daewoo Precision Industries branch of the Daewoo Corporation, the K5 pistol is now standard sidearm of the armed forces of South Korea. The basic 9mm K5 is sold as Daewoo DP-51, its compact variant is sold as DP-51c, and the variant in the .40SW is sold as DH-40. These pistols are well made and shoot well.

Daewoo K5 / DP51 pistol is short recoil operated, locked breech weapon. It uses a conventional Browning-type locking system, with two lugs on the barrel engaging cuts inside the slide. Locking and unlocking is controlled by the cam-shaped lug at the bottom of the barrel. Frame of the pistol is made from aluminum alloy; all other parts are made from steel. Trigger is of “triple action” type. This means that other than traditional double or single action fire modes it has “fast action” mode, apparently borrowed from FN’s GP “Fast Action” pistol. In this mode hammer is cocked by the cycle of the slide, then it is pushed forward by the pressure on the hammer head. In this position, the main spring remains cocked, so only light pressure on the trigger is necessary to recock the hammer and fire the gun in the “double action manner”. Or, alternatively, hammer can be recocked manually to be fired in single action for maximum first-shot accuracy. Sights are fixed, with the rear sight dovetailed to the slide. Magazines are of double stack type; proprietary magazines hold 13 rounds, but DP-51 also can use Smith-Wesson 5906 magazines, which will slightly protrude from the bottom of the grip.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Sig 556 Classic - Sig Sauer, AR Mags, .223/5.56mm, Bayonet - NIB, New Gun Legislation coming TUESDAY
postcontent:
The Sig Sauer 556 Classic is a semi-automatic centerfire rifle made by the SigArms company in Exeter, NH. The gas-piston system of this rifle is similar to the AK-47, it uses a gas port forward in the barrel to force a long piston op-rod backwards; discharging the casing and loading a new round. The gas system has two settings, both of them appear to be of the same port size (providing a dirty-port alternative; in case of a gas system failure)

It’s chambered in .223/5.56mm and has a 1 in 7″ twist rate barrel. It’s capable of using AR-15 type magazines that are widely available in a range of capacities. The rifle has an “HK-Style” sight system (rotary distance adjustable rear, post-in-ring up front) with an additional rear sight integrated into the rail system (emergency backup only; it’s a very flimsy piece of hinged steel). The rifle has ambidextrous safety selectors, and an AR-15 style magazine release.

The grip angle is a bit more swept back, and a longer reach to the safety selector, than the AR-15. The reciprocating charging handle is located on the right side of the weapon, directly attached to the bolt. The trigger is a two-stage of pull, that breaks cleanly and evenly with repeatable first stage take-up every time. The Stock is a plastic Swiss-Style side folder, similar to that of the Sig SG 550 rifles. The bold hold/release is in a similar location to the AR-15, but operates on an extended pivot system comparatively.

Comes with:

1 -Sig 556 Rifle
1 -Box
1 -Paperwork
1 -30rd Metal Sig Sauer Mag
1 -30rd Lancer Smoke colored mag (in picture)
1 -Extended safety lever (factory safety lever included as well)
1 -Swiss Bayonet with scabbard and Lug (installed)

I'm looking to acquire a M1 Carbine.  Preferrably one of the CMP USGI carbines, without an import stamp.  Not interested in commercial copies such as Iver Johnson, Universal, Plainfield, or Auto Ordinance, or carbines that have been modified by having scope mounts added or parts cut off. I'm also looking for a M1903A3, which is the version of the M1903 with the rear peep sight.  Just like with the M1 Carbine, I'm looking for a non-import marked rifle in original configuration, made by Remington or Smith Corona.  Not interested in cut down or sporterized deer rifles, rifles built from commercial receivers (like National Ordnance), or rewelded drill rifles.  Price range is $500-$700. 

I can buy outright for the right price, or I have various rifles for partial trade, such as a  Czech Mauser Vz. 24 in 8mm Mauser (trade value ~$300), or Mosin Nagant M91/30 rifle or M44 carbine in 7.62x54R (trade value ~$150 for the rifle or ~$250 for the carbine). I'm willing to drive a reasonable distance to make the deal.  And I have a C&R FFL, so out of state deals in Northeast Oklahoma, Southeast Kansas, or Southwest Missouri are fine.

title: For Sale:  BRP Machined UHP-15 AR Complete Lower Not Colt DPMS Rock River
postcontent: The BRP Corp Ultra High Precision (UHP) 15 is specifically made to meet the need for a rugged and precise lower receiver for today's AR style rifles. They hold half of the mil-spec tolerance to ensure exact fits and smooth function. These lower receivers are machined from forged 7075 aluminum blanks using only the best tooling available. title: For Sale/Trade:  Sig 556 Classic Rifle - Sig Sauer Gas Piston AR Mags - .223/5.56mm - NIB, New Gun Legislation coming TUESDAY
postcontent:
The Sig Sauer 556 Classic is a semi-automatic centerfire rifle made by the SigArms company in Exeter, NH. The gas-piston system of this rifle is similar to the AK-47, it uses a gas port forward in the barrel to force a long piston op-rod backwards; discharging the casing and loading a new round. The gas system has two settings, both of them appear to be of the same port size (providing a dirty-port alternative; in case of a gas system failure)

It’s chambered in .223/5.56mm and has a 1 in 7″ twist rate barrel. It’s capable of using AR-15 type magazines that are widely available in a range of capacities. The rifle has an “HK-Style” sight system (rotary distance adjustable rear, post-in-ring up front) with an additional rear sight integrated into the rail system (emergency backup only; it’s a very flimsy piece of hinged steel). The rifle has ambidextrous safety selectors, and an AR-15 style magazine release.

The grip angle is a bit more swept back, and a longer reach to the safety selector, than the AR-15. The reciprocating charging handle is located on the right side of the weapon, directly attached to the bolt. The trigger is a two-stage of pull, that breaks cleanly and evenly with repeatable first stage take-up every time. The Stock is a plastic Swiss-Style side folder, similar to that of the Sig SG 550 rifles. The bold hold/release is in a similar location to the AR-15, but operates on an extended pivot system comparatively.

title: For Sale:  Vintage Stevens-Browning Model 621 12ga TRUE TAKEDOWN Pump
postcontent: Here we have a nice old Stevens-Browning Model 621 pump action 12 gauge, 32" full choke, the pump gun that is now getting a bunch of new attention, as they are true take down models that separate the barrel and magazine from the receiver/stock, a John Browning design originally from the early 1900's. (This is listed as a Savage Arms gun as Stevens is not offered as a choice of attribute)This old rascal has seen action from an uncle that last carried it afield in maybe 1975, and it has the typical cosmetic and field wear and tear of guns that are now maybe 70 years old. The serial numbers match, 110XX, but I have no idea when this one was made. The grip and stock caps are origiinal. Forearm and stock checkering is crisp. The model 621 was the deluxe solid ribbed barrel upgrade to the model 620.  Not a lot of blue remains, as shown, and the barrel exterior surface rusted long ago leaving the familiar brown patina that is normal of old firearms.  Bore is shiny. This gun loads,cycles and ejects fine, action is smooth and the firing pin dents an inert shell primer just fine, but I would recommend a gunsmith inspect any semi-vintage firearm like this one before use. Mag tube capacity is 5 rounds.My plan was to shorten the barrel to 19" to make this into something that can easily and quickly break down as shown into a little 20"X 2"X 6" pack or bug out bag for end of the world prepping or into a quick and handy Home Defense weapon. Plans have changed and I will leave this old dude to you and your plan. I have tried to show the worst of the flaws and I have seen far newer guns in far worse condition.
